About R

  • R is an object-oriented programming language
    • Data
    • Procedures
  • Objects procedures can access and modify the data fields of objects.
  • If you see a + means a parenthesis or bracket is open.
  • R is case sensitive.
  • Use / in path names. Not \.

Basic concepts

A toy example

N_pop <- 1000
X1 <- rnorm(N_pop, 3, 1)
Y0 <- abs(rnorm(N_pop, 5, 2)) #+ 1.5*X1 + 0.4*X1^2
Y1 <- Y0 + rnorm(N_pop, 3, 1)
TE <- Y1 - Y0
ATE <- mean(TE)
nboots <- 1000
ATE_est <- ATT <- rep(NA, nboots)
for (i in 1:nboots){
  # pscore <- abs((X1 - min(X1))/(max(X1) - min(X1)))
  # D <- rbinom(N, 1, pscore)
  D <- rbinom(N_pop, 1, 0.3)
  # D <- rep(0, N_pop)
  # D[sample(N_pop, 500)] <- 1
  Y <- D*Y1 + (1-D)*Y0
  data.pop <- data.frame(Y=Y, D=D)
  ATT[i] <- mean(TE[D==1])
  ATE_est[i] <- mean(Y[D==1]) - mean(Y[D==0])
}
plot(density(ATE_est), main = "Bias of the group-mean-difference estimator", xlab = "ATE estimates", xlim = c(0, 10))
abline(v = ATE, lty = 2)

cat("The true ATE is", ATE, ", and the average of ATE estimates is", mean(ATE_est), "\n")
## The true ATE is 3.009998 , and the average of ATE estimates is 3.002368
cat("The sampling variance of ATE estimates is", var(ATE_est), "\n")
## The sampling variance of ATE estimates is 0.0190963
plot(density(ATT), main = "ATE vs. ATT", xlab = "ATT", xlim = c(0, 10))
abline(v = ATE, lty = 2)

nboots <- 1000
D <- rep(0, N_pop)
D[sample(N_pop, 500)] <- 1
Y <- D*Y1 + (1-D)*Y0
ATE_original <- mean(Y[D==1]) - mean(Y[D==0])

ATE_boot <- rep(NA, nboots)
for (i in 1:nboots){
  D_boot <- rep(0, N_pop)
  D_boot[sample(N_pop, 500)] <- 1
  ATE_boot[i] <- mean(Y[D_boot==1]) - mean(Y[D_boot==0])
}
plot(density(ATE_boot), main = "Fisher's Randomization Test", xlab = "ATE estimates", xlim = c(-2, 6))
abline(v = ATE_original, lty = 2)

cat("The 95% confidence interval under the null distribution is", quantile(ATE_boot, c(0.025, 0.975)), "\n")
## The 95% confidence interval under the null distribution is -0.3208454 0.3467824

## The total variance of ATE estimates is 0.1588628
## The variance of ATE estimates due to design is 0.1517845
## The variance of ATE estimates due to sampling is 0.009587187
## The average variance estimates is 0.1590043

Causal inference as a sampling problem

  • In the classic sampling world, we want to estimate the population mean (\(n\)) via the average of a random sample (\(N\)).
  • We use a dummy variable \(S_i\) to denote whether \(i\) is included in the sample. \[ \hat{\bar Y} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N Y_i = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^n S_i Y_i \]
  • When the sampling probability (\(p_i = P(S_i = 1)\)) varies across individuals, we need some adjustment when conducting the estimation: \[ \hat{\bar Y} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{Y_i}{p_i} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \frac{S_i Y_i}{p_i} \]
  • This is the so-called Horvitz-Thompson estimator.
  • For higher efficiency, we can also use the Hajek estimator: \[ \hat{\bar Y} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N\frac{Y_i}{p_i}}{\sum_{i=1}^N\frac{1}{p_i}} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^n \frac{S_i Y_i}{p_i}}{\sum_{i=1}^n \frac{S_i}{p_i}} \]
  • In causal inference, we want to estimate two population means: \(\bar Y(1)\) and \(\bar Y(0)\).
  • Assignment can be seen as a second sampling: \[ \hat{\bar Y}(1) = \frac{1}{N_1} \sum_{i=1}^{N_1} Y_i = \frac{1}{N_1} \sum_{i=1}^N D_i Y_i \] \[ \hat{\bar Y}(0) = \frac{1}{N_0} \sum_{i=1}^{N_0} Y_i = \frac{1}{N_0} \sum_{i=1}^N (1-D_i) Y_i \]
  • We can also construct the Horvitz-Thompson estimator and Hajek estimator in causal inference: \[ \widehat{ATE}_{HT} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{D_i Y_i}{p_i} - \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{(1-D_i) Y_i}{1-p_i} \]

\[ \widehat{ATE}_{HA} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{D_i Y_i}{p_i}}{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{D_i}{p_i}} - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{(1-D_i) Y_i}{1-p_i}}{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{1-D_i}{1-p_i}} \]

A special case: Bernoulli trial with equal probability

  • How to estimate the ATE in this case?
  • Now the two estimators become: \[ \widehat{ATE}_{HT} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{D_i Y_i}{p} - \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \frac{(1-D_i) Y_i}{1-p} = \frac{1}{Np} \sum_{i=1}^N D_i Y_i - \frac{1}{N(1-p)} \sum_{i=1}^N (1-D_i) Y_i \] and \[ \begin{aligned} \widehat{ATE}_{HA} = & \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{D_i Y_i}{p}}{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{D_i}{p}} - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{(1-D_i) Y_i}{1-p}}{\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{1-D_i}{1-p}} = \frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^N D_i} \sum_{i=1}^N D_i Y_i - \frac{1}{\sum_{i=1}^N (1-D_i)} \sum_{i=1}^N (1-D_i) Y_i \\ = & \frac{1}{N_1} \sum_{i=1}^N D_i Y_i - \frac{1}{N_0} \sum_{i=1}^N (1-D_i) Y_i \end{aligned} \]
